Hi all,
Recently I was reading the code in the tensor mechanics. I was confused about the "configuration" in the code. For example, the line 114-120 in ADComputeFiniteStrain.C are:
// Update strain in intermediate configuration
  _mechanical_strain[_qp] = _mechanical_strain_old[_qp] + _strain_increment[_qp];
  _total_strain[_qp] = _total_strain_old[_qp] + total_strain_increment;

  // Rotate strain to current configuration
  _mechanical_strain[_qp].rotate(_rotation_increment[_qp]);
  _total_strain[_qp].rotate(_rotation_increment[_qp]);

What do the "intermediate configuration" and the "current configuration" mean? Why should the mechanical and total strain be "rotated" but the strain increment don't need to? Does any one know this? Thanks.
Best Regards,
Xiaobei

Hi All,
Please help me in understanding of the INSFVMixingLengthReynoldsStress kernel.
I have the following questions:


Variable _axis_index represents the momentum equation component for which we are using the kernel (x, y, or z). What does then variable _index denote?


Let's say, _axis_index=0 (i.e., we are solving for the x component) and the problem is 3D.


Then we first compute the following quantity:
norm_strain_rate = grad_u(0) * _normal(0) + grad_v(0) * _normal(1) + grad_w(0) * _normal(2)
i.e.,
norm_strain_rate = du/dx * nx + dv/dx * ny + dw/dx * nz
And second we add:
const ADRealVectorValue & var_grad = _index == 0 ? grad_u : (_index == 1 ? grad_v : grad_w);
norm_strain_rate += var_grad * _normal;

It is not clear for me what is the result of these 2 operations? Seems that after the first one we are getting a vector, and then add to it tensor?

What is going on in this part of the code?

  if (_face_type == FaceInfo::VarFaceNeighbors::ELEM ||
      _face_type == FaceInfo::VarFaceNeighbors::BOTH)
  {
    const auto dof_number = _face_info->elem().dof_number(_sys.number(), _var.number(), 0);
    // norm_strain_rate is a linear combination of degrees of freedom so it's safe to straight-up
    // index into the derivatives vector at the dof we care about
    _ae = norm_strain_rate.derivatives()[dof_number];
    _ae *= -rho * eddy_diff;
  }
  if (_face_type == FaceInfo::VarFaceNeighbors::NEIGHBOR ||
      _face_type == FaceInfo::VarFaceNeighbors::BOTH)
  {
    const auto dof_number = _face_info->neighbor().dof_number(_sys.number(), _var.number(), 0);
    _an = norm_strain_rate.derivatives()[dof_number];
    _an *= rho * eddy_diff;
  }


What is going on in this part of the code?

void
INSFVMixingLengthReynoldsStress::gatherRCData(const FaceInfo & fi)
{
  if (skipForBoundary(fi))
    return;

  _face_info = &fi;
  _normal = fi.normal();
  _face_type = fi.faceType(_var.name());

  processResidualAndJacobian(computeStrongResidual() * (fi.faceArea() * fi.faceCoord()));

  if (_face_type == FaceInfo::VarFaceNeighbors::ELEM ||
      _face_type == FaceInfo::VarFaceNeighbors::BOTH)
    _rc_uo.addToA(&fi.elem(), _index, _ae * (fi.faceArea() * fi.faceCoord()));
  if (_face_type == FaceInfo::VarFaceNeighbors::NEIGHBOR ||
      _face_type == FaceInfo::VarFaceNeighbors::BOTH)
    _rc_uo.addToA(fi.neighborPtr(), _index, _an * (fi.faceArea() * fi.faceCoord()));
}


The kernel returns "the force due to the Reynolds stress term":

-1 * rho * eddy_diff * norm_strain_rate;
what is the structure of this term, I mean if it is a tensor, what is its dimension?
